"{\"uid\": \"standard.co.uk-sport-sport-olympics-paris-olympics-2024-controversial-moments-cheating-china-seine-gender-b1174775.html\", \"text\": \"To use the search feature, we need your consent to load Google Custom Search, which may use cookies or similar technologies. Please click 'Allow and Continue' below to enable search. See our privacy policy for more information.  Sport|Olympics  PreviousOlympicgames have been no stranger to controversy and this year's have not been any different.  Fromgenderdebates to questioned victories, here are some of the most talked about moments.  The most recent Olympics controversy involves Great Britain men's swimmerAdam Peatyhitting out at swimmers \\\"cheating\\\"in the game as he questioned the legitimacy of China's victory in Sunday's medley relay.  Great Britain were placed fourth by a Chinese quartet, two of whom tested positive for a banned substance in the lead-up to the Tokyo Olympics. The incident was only brought to light this year in a New York Times investigation.  One of the competitors, Qin Haiyang, also allegedly tested positive for a different performance-enhancing drug several years earlier but he had escaped punishment on contamination grounds.  Following his team's defeat on Sunday, Peaty called for fairness in the game. He said: \\\"I think you know that truth in your heart. If you touch and you know that you arecheating, you are not winning, right?  \\\"For me, if you have been on that and you have been 'contaminated' twice, I think as an honourable person you should be out of the sport.  \\\"I do not want to paint a whole nation or group of people with one brush, I think that's very unfair. But there have been two cases of it and it's very disappointing.\\\"  A 29-year-old beach volleyball player Steven van de Velde was sentenced to four years in prison in 2016 after pleading guilty to raping a 12-year-old girl when he was 19.  Hottest hotel openings for 2026  London named as 'the best food city in the world'  Bridgerton stars attend season four premiere in Paris  Incredible days out and trips for autumn and winter  The Olympics have drawn criticism following his inclusion in the Netherlands team forParis, with van de Velde staying in a secret location rather than the athletes' village.  Algerian boxerImane Kheliffound herself in the midst of controversy last Thursday after Italian fighter Angela Cariniabandoned her boutwith Khelif  less than a minute after it started.  Carini, who has since apologised for the level of scrutiny she generated, explained she had never been hit so hard and decided to withdraw because of the intense pain in her nose. The incident amassed millions of views on social media, and triggered responses from celebrities including YouTuber Logan Paul.  Although questions about Khelif'sgendercontinue to swirl online, it has been revealed that Khelif was born a woman and, until last year, had always competed in women's boxing categories without controversy or attention.  In an interview with SNTV the Algerian athlete said in Arabic: \\\"I send a message to all the people of the world to uphold the Olympic principles and the Olympic Charter, to refrain from bullying all athletes, because this has effects, massive effects.  \\\"It can destroy people, it can kill people's thoughts, spirit and mind. It can divide people. And because of that, I ask them to refrain from bullying.\\\"  Triathlontraining in theRiver Seinewas last week cancelled for a second successive day because of the water quality.  It followed growing concerns over the high levels of sewage in the water in the lead-up to theParis Olympics.  A Belgian athlete has since been forced to pull out of the triathlon, after reportedly contracting E.coli.  Belgium have not confirmed whether Michel's illness is a direct consequence of having swum in the Seine but one Belgian newspaper has reported that the 35-year-old has been too ill to compete in Monday's mixed triathlon relay.  Sunday's 100m men's final left scores of viewers looking at US athlete Noah Lyles, unsure if he had won gold after what was an extremely tight race. Lyles had crossed the finish line next to his closest rival in the shortest time difference since at least Moscow 1980. Lyles finished first at 9.784 seconds compared with Jamaica's Kishane Thompson who completed the race in 9.789 seconds.  Lyles' decision to lean forward at the end of the race, propelling his chest over the finish line, was the difference in the extremely close call on the purple track at the Stade de France.  Per field and track rules, it is the first athlete whose torso reaches the finish line first is declared the winner.  An Egyptian Olympic volleyball duohave gone viralfollowing a decision to defiantly compete fully clothed in the\\u00a0Olympic\\u00a0Games, despite ahijabban France has imposed on its own athletes.  The announcement had led to huge controversy but one of the players, Doaa Elghobashy, has defended her decision to play with the hijab rather than a bikini like her Spanish opponents.  Following Egypt's 2-0 loss to Spain, the pair were seen embracing, sporting a long-sleeve top, leggings and headscarf.  \\\"I want to play in my hijab, she wants to play in a bikini - everything is okay, if you want to be naked or wear a hijab. Just respect all different cultures and religions,\\\" Elghobashy told\\u00a0Expressen.  \\\"I do not tell you to wear a hijab and you do not tell me to wear a bikini. No one can tell me how to dress.  \\\"It's a free country, everyone should be allowed to do what they want.\\\"  MORE ABOUT  Have your say...  1  Crime  Fight breaks out on Elizabeth line train after youths told to stop vaping by middle-aged passenger  Fight breaks out on Elizabeth line after youths told to stop vaping  2  Football  Liverpool XI vs Brighton: Starting lineup, confirmed team news, injury latest for Premier League today  Liverpool XI vs Brighton: Starting lineup and confirmed team news  3  UK  Flights alert: UK issues global travel disruption warning over Donald Trump's Iran war  Flights alert: UK issues global travel disruption warning on Iran war  4  Lifestyle  Horoscope today: Your daily guide for Saturday, March 21, 2026  Horoscope today: Your daily guide for Saturday, March 21, 2026  5  Football  Arsenal XI vs Man City: Confirmed team news, predicted lineup, injury latest for Carabao Cup final  Arsenal XI vs Man City: Confirmed team news and predicted lineup\"}"